This example demonstrates a stateful PCE (Path Computation Element, RFC 5440/
8231) controlling an RSVP-TE MPLS core: an ingress LSR delegates a running
LSP to a remote PCE, and later a bandwidth change in the network makes the
PCE recompute and push a genuinely different path onto that LSP via a PCUpd
-- the whole PCEP/stateful-PCE feature set (Workstream F4) working together
in one runnable network, rather than in the isolated pieces
tests/module/pcep_*.test each exercise individually. See those tests first
for the underlying protocol machinery this example's scenario reuses almost
verbatim.

Topology
--------

A 6-LSR RSVP-TE core, plus a seventh node that runs the PCE:

```
                     LSR2 --- LSR3
                    /   600kbps  \
host1 -- LSR1 --                  -- LSR6 -- host2
                    \  10 Mbps   /   \
                     LSR4 --- LSR5     PceRouter
```

LSR1 (ingress) reaches LSR6 (egress) over two parallel two-hop branches: the
LSR2-LSR3 branch (600 kbps per link, metric 1 per hop -- cheaper by TE
metric) and the LSR4-LSR5 branch (10 Mbps per link, metric 5 per hop --
plenty of spare capacity, but the more expensive route). PceRouter hangs off
LSR6 on its own leaf link and runs the ~Pce; it is deliberately NOT
co-located with LSR6 itself (mirroring tests/module/pcep_fallback.test's own
placement rationale), so the PCE's own reachability is never entangled with
either data-plane branch. host1 and host2 are the traffic endpoints.

Router IDs are picked automatically ("auto": the highest interface address
per router) -- LSR1=10.0.4.1, LSR2=10.0.2.1, LSR3=10.0.3.1, LSR4=10.0.5.1,
LSR5=10.0.6.1, LSR6=10.0.8.1, PceRouter=10.0.7.2. LSR1's ~Pcc connects to
PceRouter's routerId (10.0.7.2) over the genuinely multi-hop route
~LinkStateRouting installs; LSR1's own ~Pcc.localAddress is pinned to its own
routerId (10.0.4.1), not left to an arbitrary outgoing interface, for the
same reason documented in ~Pcc's own "localAddress" parameter and exercised
by every pcep_*.test: ~Ted/~LinkStateRouting (like a real IGP) only
guarantees network-wide reachability to each router's own routerId, not to
its individual per-link addresses.

Scenario
--------

1. At t=0, tunnel 1 (lspid 100, 50 kbps, permanent) is configured at LSR1
   with computeEro=true, computationMode="pce", delegate=true. Its first few
   createIngressPSB() attempts legitimately fail until the PCEP session (over
   real, multi-hop TCP, including one SYN retransmit) reaches OPERATIONAL,
   around t~5.3s in this run; the PCE then computes the plain-cheapest route
   -- the LSR2-LSR3 branch -- and LSR1 reports the established LSP to the PCE
   as a delegated one (PCRpt).
2. At t=7s, a scenario add-session brings up tunnel 2 (lspid 200, 520 kbps,
   permanent, an EXPLICIT hand-configured route via the SAME LSR2-LSR3
   branch) -- an ordinary, independently signaled admission request that
   never touches the PCE's CSPF at all. Combined with tunnel 1's own 50 kbps,
   the LSR2-LSR3 branch now carries 570 of its 600 kbps capacity: only 30
   kbps free, no longer enough for a hypothetical fresh 50 kbps request.
   Tunnel 1 itself is completely undisturbed by this -- CAC only ever blocks
   NEW requests, it never preempts or re-checks an already-established
   reservation.
3. At t=9s, a ScenarioManager "pce-reoptimize" command (naming tunnel 1's
   PLSP-ID, 1, explicitly rather than "all" -- tunnel 2 is also delegated,
   since "delegate" applies to every ingress path regardless of how its own
   route was obtained, and reoptimizing "all" would also (correctly) migrate
   it, muddying this example's point) tells the PCE to recompute tunnel 1's
   path. Re-running CSPF with tunnel 1's original inputs (50 kbps) now finds
   the LSR2-LSR3 branch infeasible (only 30 kbps free) and returns the
   LSR4-LSR5 branch instead -- a genuinely different route -- so the PCE
   sends a PCUpd. LSR1 applies it via make-before-break: a fresh replacement
   lspid (201) is signaled using the PCE-supplied ERO directly (no fresh
   CSPF/PCReq round-trip -- the ERO is already a full strict route), the
   classifier's FEC entry is rebound to it once its ingress label is
   installed, the old lspid (100) is torn down, and the cutover is reported
   back to the PCE (PCRpt, echoing the PCUpd's srpId).

Traffic is a single periodic UDP flow, host1 -> host2 (128-byte datagrams
every 20 ms, well under both branches' capacity), running for the whole
14-second simulation, including across the cutover.

How to observe it
------------------

Run with Cmdenv (the default in this ini) and grep the output for the PCEP
exchange. Actually confirmed by running this example:

```
[INFO]  PCEP session with 10.0.4.1 is now OPERATIONAL
[DETAIL] PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.0.8.1, lspid=100): 10.0.2.1, 10.0.3.1, 10.0.8.1
[INFO]  reporting delegated LSP UP to PCE (plspId=1, lspid=100, ERO 10.0.2.1, 10.0.3.1, 10.0.8.1)
...
[INFO]  adding new session into database                          # tunnel 2, t=7s
...
[INFO]  processing <pce-reoptimize> command...                    # t=9s
[INFO]  pce-reoptimize: found a better path for PLSP-ID 1 (10.0.5.1, 10.0.6.1, 10.0.8.1), sending PCUpd
[INFO]  PCUpd sent to 10.0.4.1 (srpId=1, plspId=1, ERO with 3 hop(s))
[INFO]  PCUpd received from PCE (srpId=1, plspId=1, ERO with 3 hop(s))
[INFO]  PCUpd received for PLSP-ID 1: re-routing lspid=100 via make-before-break with the PCE-supplied ERO (10.0.5.1, 10.0.6.1, 10.0.8.1)
[INFO]  make-before-break cutover: lspid=201 is up, switching traffic away from lspid=100
[INFO]  make-before-break cutover: rebinding fec id 1 from lspid 100 to lspid 201, in-label 18
[INFO]  sending PathTear to 10.0.2.1
```

10.0.2.1/10.0.3.1 are LSR2/LSR3's routerIds (the original, cheap branch);
10.0.5.1/10.0.6.1 are LSR4/LSR5's routerIds (the replacement, expensive
branch); 10.0.8.1 is LSR6's (the shared egress, unchanged). host2's
"packetReceived:count" scalar (699, out of 700 sent over the 14s run) at the
end of the run confirms traffic kept flowing end to end across the entire
scenario, including the mid-flight reroute.

What this models vs. real PCEP / stateful PCE
-----------------------------------------------

Session establishment, stateless path computation, and stateful delegation
are modeled at the level of detail described in ~Pce's and ~Pcc's own class
documentation (also summarized in the sibling tests/module/pcep_*.test
files' own descriptions):

- **Session FSM** (RFC 5440 Section 6.2, minimal subset): Open/Keepalive
  exchange to OPERATIONAL, KeepAlive Time negotiated as the smaller of both
  sides' proposals, DeadTimer-based liveness using each side's OWN
  advertised value. No Open error negotiation/retry (RFC 5440 Section 6.3).
- **Stateless path computation** (PCReq/PCRep, RFC 5440 Section 6.5/6.6):
  the PCE runs the identical bandwidth-pruning CSPF (Ted::calculateShortestPath())
  ~RsvpTe's own local computation already uses, just rooted at the
  requesting PCC and reached over PCEP instead of called in-process. Fixed
  objective function only (minimize total TE metric subject to a bandwidth
  constraint) -- no PCEP objective-function TLV negotiation.
- **Stateful delegation and PCE-initiated reoptimization** (RFC 8231
  Sections 5-6): a delegated LSP's state is reported via PCRpt whenever it
  changes; the PCE recomputes a delegated LSP's path and pushes a PCUpd
  ONLY on an explicit operator/ScenarioManager "pce-reoptimize" command
  (see ~Pce's own class documentation for why a TED-change-triggered
  version was considered and rejected as harder to make deterministic) --
  this example demonstrates exactly that trigger. No RFC 8231 Section 5.6
  State Synchronization: if a PCC's session bounces and reconnects, the PCE
  does not re-learn which LSPs are still delegated to it.
- **Controller-death fallback** (RFC 8231 Section 5.2 state timeout) exists
  in this model -- a PCC whose PCEP session dies and stays dead falls back
  to local (non-PCE) computation for every LSP it had delegated, after a
  configurable grace period -- but is NOT demonstrated by this example
  (this example is about the PCE doing its job, not failing); see
  tests/module/pcep_fallback.test for that scenario in full.

Explicitly NOT modeled (out of scope for this workstream):

- **No BGP-LS feed.** The PCE's TED is a direct, omniscient module-path
  reference (~tedModule) into the SAME ~Ted every router already maintains
  via ~LinkStateRouting -- not learned via BGP-LS or any other northbound
  topology feed. This is the same category of simplification as ~Ted's own
  initializeTED() omniscience used elsewhere in this codebase (e.g. by
  ~RsvpTe's own local CSPF).
- **No multi-PCE / H-PCE** (RFC 6805 hierarchical PCE). Exactly one PCE, one
  PCC-to-PCE session per PCC; no PCE-to-PCE communication, no parent/child
  PCE delegation, no PCE discovery (RFC 5088/5089).
- **No PCEP-over-TLS** (RFC 8253). Sessions run over plain TCP.
- **No P2MP paths** (RFC 8306). Every LSP modeled is point-to-point.
- **No association groups** (RFC 8697/8745). No cross-LSP association TLVs
  of any kind (protection groups, policy groups, etc).
- **No SRv6/segment-routed PCUpd** (RFC 8664 full SR-PCE support). SR-mode
  PCUpd application was descoped during this workstream's Phase 3 -- only
  RSVP-TE mode (a full strict hop-by-hop ERO of routerId hops) is modeled;
  every LSP in this example is a plain RSVP-TE LSP.
- **No PCE-initiated LSPs** (RFC 8281). Every LSP here is PCC-initiated
  (configured via the static traffic.xml/scenario add-session, same as any
  non-PCEP ~RsvpTe deployment) and merely delegated to the PCE after the
  fact; the PCE never creates or deletes an LSP on its own initiative.
- **No objective-function TLV negotiation** (RFC 5541). The PCE always
  optimizes the same fixed objective (minimum TE metric, bandwidth-feasible)
  -- there is no way for a PCC to request, e.g., minimum load or maximum
  bandwidth instead.

Simplifications inherited from ~RsvpTe/~Ted generally (not specific to this
workstream): the SID/TED information is static, network-wide configuration
with no partial/incremental views; there is no fast-reroute/protection
beyond what ~Ted's own shortest-path recomputation provides once a failure
is noticed.
